We have ways to extract configuration using strong types, via things like `requireNumber`, etc. I am hoping that this becomes even more first class as part of https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/issues/1052, where presumably part of declaring a package's config schema will include the types of individual variables. This will help cut down on boilerplate when extracting config values.

During conversion of CloudFormation, I have found a few specific schema types that we don't currently support. Namely

* Regex patterns
* Enum lists of legal values
* Min/max length constraints
* Min/max number values

See https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/parameters-section-structure.html.

As part of https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/issues/1052, we should consider them. But even absent it, we may want to support helper functions that just reduce boilerplate.

As one specific instance, this

```typescript
export const dbName = config.get("dbName") || "MyDatabase";
if (!/[a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9]*/.test(dbName)) {
    throw new Error("dbName must begin with a letter and contain only alphanumeric characters");
} else if (dbName.length < 1 || dbName.length > 64) {
    throw new Error("dbName must between 1-64 characters, inclusively")
}
```

could have become

```typescript
export const dbName = config.get("dbName",
    { pattern: "[a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9]", minLength: 1, maxLength: 64} }) || "MyDatabase";
```

@jasonzliang requested api that essentially performs map operation on a set of data, waits for results and returns them. 
@jasonzliang , could you clarify what kind of return results are you expecting? 
We can either use text output, or on arbitrary pickleable object (the latter one being more generic)

Currently, we have (with some bits cut out)

```
message TensorShapeProto {
  ...
  repeated Dimension dim = 1;
}

message TypeProto {
  message Tensor {
    ...
    optional TensorShapeProto shape = 2;
  }
  ...
}
```

In theory, we can represent "no shape information" by having `has_shape()` be false, and we can represent "scalar" as "`has_shape()` is true, and `dim_size()` is zero".

However, the C++ protobuf api doesn't distinguish between these two cases (it can be done in python, for example see https://gist.github.com/anderspapitto/f772b697ced651ff3aefba0dbcab02ee)

So we may need to add an additional field to the protobuf definitions to represent "no shape information"
